summary: This is a U.S. Department of Justice foreign travel questionnaire for an Assistant U.S. Attorney (AUSA) from the Southern District of New York (SDNY) traveling to Stockholm, Sweden from February 3-6, 2020. The purpose is to interview a witness (Jane Doe) in the ongoing, sensitive investigation into Jeffrey Epstein, with Ghislaine Maxwell identified as a subject.

persons.name: Jeffrey Epstein
persons.context: The case being investigated is "In re Jeffrey Epstein." He is the central figure of the investigation for which the travel is being conducted.

persons.name: Ghislaine Maxwell
persons.context: Identified as a subject of the investigation, believed to be a citizen of the U.S., U.K., and France.

persons.name: Jane Doe
persons.context: A Swedish national to be interviewed and debriefed in Stockholm as part of the Epstein investigation.

connections.description: Both are named as subjects/targets in the same ongoing criminal investigation (USAO # 2018R01618).
Maxwell is a subject of an investigation for which Jane Doe is being interviewed as a witness, implying a potential victim-witness relationship.
Epstein is the central subject of an investigation for which Jane Doe is being interviewed as a witness, implying a potential victim-witness relationship.

events.title: Planned Travel to Sweden for Witness Interview
events.description: An AUSA from SDNY plans to travel from New York to Stockholm, Sweden to interview and debrief a witness (Jane Doe) in the Jeffrey Epstein investigation.

keyFacts: In February 2020, the U.S. Attorney's Office for the Southern District of New York was actively investigating Jeffrey Epstein, with Ghislaine Maxwell explicitly named as a subject.
The investigation (USAO # 2018R01618) was described as "ongoing and very sensitive."
Prosecutors traveled internationally to Sweden to interview a witness identified only as "Jane Doe, Swedish," indicating the global scope of the investigation.
The document confirms foreign authorities (likely Swedish) had cleared the visit and were prepared to cooperate with U.S. investigators.
The travel was officially funded by the USAO-SDNY, not by any external source.
